"<div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nPerson Note\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\n<strong>Notes written by Lesley Barber</strong>\n</p>\n<p>\n\"She was my maternal grandmother. I don\u2019t know an awful lot about her. And most of that second hand from my mother. There were 6 children [listed elsewhere] and they were very poor. Her father is said to have drunk and left. He died in 1901. Her mother died in 1928 missing my birth by about 3 years. They were both buried in Crediton church graveyard.\n</p>\n<p>\nJohn and I went to Devon and Cornwall on holiday one year [2001] we went to the church &nbsp;to see what we could find out &nbsp;and a very helpful gentleman, Mr. Robin Langhorn, &nbsp;told us the graves were not there anymore but they had a plan of the churchyard and a note of the dates of death of &nbsp;Harriet and James.\n</p>\n<p>\nBessie and her siblings had to go to bed when their clothes were washed as they only had one set - which seems a little odd and according to Gill [my sister] our g.grandmother took in washing.<br />\nBessie also cleaned the school house when she was 12 in exchange for schooling. There were 2 schools and it would help to know which school it was to see if there was any more information from there.<br />\nFrom the 1881 census some of the children, including Bessie were in the workhouse [Bessie would have been 5] Perhaps one of the siblings was being born?<br />\nLater Bessie went to London in service and eventually met my grandfather. The story is that he had to hide in the coal cellar when he came courting as callers were not allowed! &nbsp; But very recently I have been talking to Ivy, now 90, [Charlie\u2019s widow] who told me that the people with whom Bessie was in service sent her for cookery class sat Kensington which was where she met my grandfather so they must have thought a lot of her. I have a half tea service that was hers. I remember Alice and Dorothy dividing the full set when they had to sort out the house after Bessie died. I often wonder if it was given to Bessie when she married by the people with whom she was in service.\n</p>\n<p>\nGill and I used to go and see Bessie and William - we called them big Nana and Granddad to distinguish them from our paternal little Nana and Granddad.\n</p>\n<p>\nMy main memory of Big Nana is that she used to sit in the chair by the fire in the room at 7, Windsor Avenue and say she had a bone in her leg and couldn\u2019t walk far! &nbsp;She used to like listening to Mrs. Dale\u2019s Diary as well. Mother and Dorothy had quite a job in the winters to get her to enough coal on the fire to keep warm! I also remember her telling us tell us she wore a bustle when she was young, that she was in service somewhere in London and Granddad hid in the cellar because they weren\u2019t allowed callers. I didn\u2019t know she had trained to be a cook. Mother told me Bessie recited the recipe for Christmas pudding to her when she was first married - so that recipe must have come from Kensington! I still use it today! Mother also told me that when Bessie came to be married our Granddad found out from his birth certificate then that his surname was Dickens and not Morris, he had been brought up by his grandparents in Kent and when they died went to live with his father [ a butcher] in London.<br />\nMy mother, Alice was born 6 &nbsp;March 1903 and Auntie Dorothy 15 September three years later, [I remember that as it is also our wedding anniversary]. I don\u2019t know the dates for Uncle Len and Uncle Charlie.\n</p>\n<p>\nWhen mother and Dorothy sorted out Nana\u2019s house they divided her pretty blue and white 12 set tea service between them. When Gill and myself did Dad\u2019s house we discovered mother had a \u00bd dozen tea service of her own as well so rather than divide either of them we tossed for which ever and I ended up with the half of mother\u2019s - I think George has the other half. I have often wondered if it was given to Nana and Granddad by the people she was in service with when she was married!\n</p>\n<p>\nIn the 1970\u2019s &nbsp;Richard was doing a project about &nbsp;Life in the Olden Days and as Mother and Dad were staying with us at the time she wrote down some of what she could remember of Bessie\u2019s Family. &nbsp;<br />\nshe had five siblings. I am in touch with the grandson of one of them - Bert - Peter Bennellick is the son of &nbsp;Jack, [mother\u2019s cousin who married Beattie], they lived quite near Auntie Dorothy so we saw quite a lot of them when we were children. Peter had an elder brother who had died as a new-born I think. Peter has two children but no grandchildren as yet. He must be about Janet\u2019s age I think.\n</p>\n<p>\nIt doesn\u2019t seem much to remember about a grandparent and just recently I have started writing my own memories for our grand children. It\u2019s so much easier on the computer than writing by hand. I haven\u2019t got very far though! Up to when we moved to Ewell!\n</p>\n<p>\nNana told us her parents [or maybe her grandparents walked from Redruth in Cornwall to Crediton because they had heard there might be work for shoemakers - Bessie\u2019s father was a shoemaker - I seem to remember the uncle [another Fred] in Crowthorne mended shoes. Dorothy and Mother took all us children there in the war when the doodlebugs came To New Malden and Ewell.\"\n</p>\n</div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nOccupation\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nOwned confectionery shop\n</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
