"<div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nOccupation\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nEngineer\n</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
"",
"<div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nPerson Note\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nJames Cleary and James Stewart Milne Paterson are an enigma that we are yet to solve; very little is known about James Stewart Milne Paterson (who is allegedly my patezrnal grandma's [Barbara McFarlane] grandfather). According to my grandma, when she was a child, she found a box of war medals in her father's [James William Paterson] cupboard that we know did not belong to him, but to a James Francis Cleary. She asked him about them, as any normal child would, but he wouldn't say anything about the medals and demanded that they be put away. She later found that he had obliterated the information from the boxes in an attempt to prevent anybody finding out about whatever had gone on between JSMP and Cleary. We have no idea who Cleary was, his relation to the family or why JSMP had the war medals of another man, only that they were almost definitely in the millitary together.\n</p>\n<p>\nJames William Paterson was very secretive about his ancestry and would never tell my grandma anything. We only know JSMP's name from JWP's birth certifiacte, and that he was in the scots guards. However, we do know that Cleary was in the Irish guards, so why JSMP (a scotsman) was in the Irish guards, remains a mystery.\n</p>\n<p>\nOur leading theory is that Alice Mary Boniwell (JSMP's 'wife') had an affair with Cleary, which drove her to her suicide. We know that AMB was married to JSMP because she was interred as a Paterson. This would explain why JWP kept the medals, even though he was cleary deeply ashamed of them; even though he didn't want anybody to find out about them, he kept them because they were his father's. Clearly (no pun intended), this is pure speculation.\n</p>\n<p>\nCurrently, the latest census avaliable is the 1911 census, because they are not releaed until 100 years have passed since the data was collected, so maybe the 1921 census will tell us something when it is released next year.\n</p>\n</div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nOccupation\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nTea dealer. It seems he went off on ships around the world dealing tea.\n</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
"<div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nPerson Note\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nFowlers was a coal merchant<br />\nJWP rejected from army because essential job.<br />\nTransprted parcels in war/ long distance driving.\n</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
"<div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nOccupation\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nIronmonger and provost\n</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
"",
"<div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nPerson Note\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nMarion's probate went to Isabella, so probably didn't have any children.\n</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
"",
"<div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nOccupation\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nArtist. Wood engraver\n</p>\n</div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nPerson Note\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nHe was in the Grenadier Guards which was a precursor to the Irish Guards.  This might explain how James Stewart Milne Paterson ended up in the Irish Guards.\n</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
