"<div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nPerson Note\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\nThere is a classic family story about a mysterious missionary that went to China and died on the boat coming home. Her picture allegedly fell off the wall on the day she died which is how the family knew. It would have taken weeks for the news to have reached then by conventional means at the time.\n</p>\n<p>\nThe story is partly true and part Chinese whispers. She did go to China as a missionary and we have the documentation containing her instructions and visas. She travelled a lot and at some point she went to Japan from China to recover from something unknown, according to letters from her family. She had friends in Canada, which is where she died suddenly aged 64. She didn't die on the boat but she did die just before returning home. \n</p>\n<p>\n&nbsp;\n</p>\n<p>\n&nbsp;\n</p>\n</div>\n<i class=\"NoteType\">\nPerson Note\n</i>\n<div class=\"grampsstylednote\">\n<p>\n\"My Dear Flo,\n</p>\n<p>\nWe were very glad to receive your letter from Japan and to know you were so much better. We trust the stay among the hills will have completely restored you and that on recommencing your work in China you may reap the benefit of the change. We have all been very much concerned about you and have often prayed for you. Lottie has many times wished she could just come over and nurse you. If the CMS committee would only have ordered you to England for a change instead of sending you to Japan, no doubt you would have appreciated the change. You have now been away for 18 months and it only seems as yestererday since we went to the docks with you. You will soon be here again and right well shall we welcome you to old England. In the meantime we pray that God will protect you from all the dangers that your life may be _ to _ in China.\n</p>\n<p>\nYou will nore by the address that I am still at Battersea. I do not suppose I shall be at this school very long. Though I like here very much the headmaster is just such another gentleman as Mr Littlewood, thoroughly kind and sympathetic towards his assistants. Of course it is too far away from home. Dulwich is such a pretty district with the parks so near that I can\u2019t think of leaving that district. Then again we have formed friendships here. It would be very lonely for Lottie were we to remove unto a strange district. A few weeks ago we were at Mrs Felthams to tea. They inquired of you and wished us to convey their kind regards and love. They were very sorry indeed to hear of your _.\n</p>\n<p>\nCousin Christina Clay from _ has been up in London for 5 weeks. She returns in a fortnight to _. She has been learning the bedding trade. Uncle _ Clay is about to start the bedding business in Wales. Sometime next month cousin Walter Ratcliffe is coming for a few days. There is to be a large cycle exhibition in London and while much us will _ the _.\n</p>\n<p>\nBoth he and his wife have had very indifferent health since they were married. Mother wrote saying she might come up along with farther at Xmas. _ I have written them to say we cannot possible do with any visitors at Xmas as we want to have a quiet time to ourselves.\n</p>\n<p>\nWe have had visitors every holiday since we were married and we both think it is time to have a change.\n</p>\n<p>\nThings are going on here much about the same. I am still very busy much evening work. Leon friend has gone to France and as I do not rush to take more penpals in addition to what I have. I have a little more time at my disposal.\n</p>\n<p>\nRenie is getting on splendidly. She walks so well and so distinctly. I wish you could just see her. Lottie is fairly well considering. _ myself I am thankful to say _ _ better. The change during _ holidays did us all good. I shall now have to bring this scribble to a close. I promised Lottie I would drop you a few lines. She is very _ _ 5C. _ _ write to you next week. She wished me not to forget your birthday. She will send you a book next week. We both wish you very many happy returns of the day. Now goodbye. Much _ regards and _ love in which Lottie forms and a lot of kisses from baby.\n</p>\n<p>\nBelieve _\n</p>\n<p>\nEver your loving Brother. Lewis Clay.\"\n</p>\n<p>\nNote that Lottie refers to Charlotte Elizabeth Turner. Flo refers to Emily Florence Turner.\n</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
